class Solution {
public:
    int miceAndCheese(vector<int>& reward1, vector<int>& reward2, int k) {
        int ans = 0;
        int n = reward1.size();
        vector<int> diffs(n);
        for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
            diffs[i] = reward1[i] - reward2[i];
        }
        sort(diffs.begin(), diffs.end());
        for (int i = 0; i < k; i++) {
            ans += diffs[i];
        }
        return ans;
    }
};
In this code, the function miceAndCheese is completed. It takes three parameters: reward1, reward2, and k. The variable ans is initialized to 0. The variable n is assigned the size of the reward1 and reward2 arrays. The vector diffs is initialized to store the difference between the rewards of the two mice. The vector diffs is sorted in ascending order. The maximum points the mice can achieve are then calculated by summing up the first k elements of the sorted diffs array. This value is returned by the function.
